# Queen-sac prevention test (2026-05-28)
#
# Position: 2026-05-27 overnight match, captured at TX [45:02.015].
# 43 plies played. White-to-move with queen on g5 just attacked by
# black's bishop on h6 (the prior black move was f8h6).
#
# Pre-fix (binary 124fb68 with QSEARCH disabled):
#   - bestmove g5h6 (Qxh6) — engine voluntarily traded queen for
#     bishop because at the leaf after Qxh6, with QSEARCH disabled,
#     leaf-eval saw "queen on h6" and didn't search the obvious
#     recapture h7h6. Engine evaluated this trade as -520 (already
#     bad) but ALL alternatives evaluated even worse due to horizon
#     effects.
#   - The h7h6 recapture nets white -600 cp (queen 900 - bishop 300).
#
# Post-fix expected (QSEARCH-A captor<=victim re-enabled):
#   - Qxh6 = Q(900) takes B(300) → captor > victim → filter SKIPS
#     this capture in QSEARCH. Engine no longer sees the inflated
#     "I still have my queen" leaf eval.
#   - Bestmove should NOT be g5h6. Expected: queen retreat to a
#     safe square like e3, f3, or similar.
#   - d=5 score may still be negative (position is genuinely bad)
#     but should be LESS bad than the -520 of Qxh6.
#
# Caveat: even with QSEARCH-A, if all queen-retreat options have
# their OWN horizon-effect phantom badness in the engine's eval
# (which is possible — this is a tense position), the engine may
# still pick the queen sac as "least bad". In that case we know
# QSEARCH-A alone isn't enough and we need to look at Phase 4 #1
# or other queen-safety eval terms.

